===Etymology 1===
From {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|abandoner|lang=fro}}, formed from {{term|à|lang=fro}} + {{term|bandon||jurisdiction, control|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|bannum||proclamation|lang=la}}, of {{etyl|gem}} origin, from {{etyl|frk|en}} ''*ban'', from {{proto|Germanic|bannan|to proclaim, command|lang=en}} (compare {{en}} {{term|ban|lang=en}}), from {{proto|Indo-European|bha-|to speak|lang=en}}. Displaced {{enm}} ''[[forleten#Middle English|forleten]]'' "to abandon" (from {{ang}} ''[[forlætan#Old English|forlǣtan]]'', ''[[anforlætan#Old English|anforlǣtan]]'') and {{enm}} ''[[forleven#Middle English|forleven]]'' "to leave behind, abandon" (from {{ang}} ''[[forlæfan#Old English|forlǣfan]]'').

====Verb====
{{en-verb}}

# {{transitive}} To [[give up]] control of, to [[surrender]].
#* Hope was overthrown, yet could not be '''abandoned'''. — I. Taylor
# {{transitive}} To leave behind, to [[desert]].
#: ''Many baby girls have been '''abandoned''' on the streets of Beijing everyday.''
# {{context|transitive|obsolete}} To [[cast out|cast]] or [[drive out]]; to [[banish]]; to [[expel]]; to [[reject]].
#* '''1594''': Being all this time '''abandoned''' from your bed. — Shakespeare, ''The Taming of the Shrew, I-ii''
# {{transitive}} To [[relinquish]] a [[claim]] to [[property]] to [[underwriter]]s.

